John Edwards: The Essential Language Skills for Global Citizens
Private schools in Scotland hold the record for academic excellence and this has continued in 2018 with yet another string of excellent test scores, further bolstered by individual and collective success in sports, art, music and other fields.
With over 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Council of Private Schools (SCIS), strive to provide the highest level of service to their students and parents.
Private schools aim to prepare their students for further education at the highest levels, for the career of their choice and for their country as global citizens.
As an education sector that can design and implement a tailored educational curriculum, we are proving how the branch of modern languages continues to be a widespread and popular choice in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, "If you speak to someone in a language they understand, your words will be heard."
If you speak to him in your own language, your words go to his heart.”
These words are a powerful reminder that we can't rely only on English when we want to build relationships with people from foreign countries.
From the results of this year's final exams, we can conclude that languages are top of the list of results, with the highest rate of passing grades among private schools.
A total of 68 percent of students who have studied foreign languages have received the maximum grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72 percent of students had received the maximum grade A in Mandarin, while 72 percent of those who studied German, 69 percent of those who studied French, and 63 percent of those who studied Spanish had also received A.
This shows that private schools in Scotland are supporting foreign languages as one of the vital skills that children and young people will undoubtedly need in the future.
Currently, the branch of foreign languages is considered as important as the branches of STEM (science, technology, engineering and mathematics) in the curricula of private schools and beyond.
A 2014 study by the United Kingdom Commission on Employment and Skills found that among the main difficulties employers encountered in filling vacancies, 17 percent of them were related to a lack of language skills.
As a result, language skills are becoming more and more essential for preparing young people for their future careers.
With the addition of jobs that require foreign language proficiency, these skills are essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the career a person chooses, if he has learned a second language, he will have real advantages in the future, as a possessor of such a long-term skill.
The ability to communicate directly with strangers will automatically position a multilingual person above the competition.
According to a YouGov survey, which included over 4,000 adults from the UK in 2013, 75 percent of them were unable to speak a foreign language well enough to conduct a conversation, and French was the only foreign language spoken by a percentage of concretely 15 people per 2 shillings.
This is why investing in language learning is important for today's children.
The mastery of many languages, especially the languages of developing countries, will give children a better chance of employment.
Within Scotland, every school will be different in terms of the languages they are taught in.
Some schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will offer languages that are considered to be most important to the UK in the 2020 perspective, such as Mandarin or Japanese.
Whatever your child's interest, there will always be a range of languages to choose from in private schools, with pedagogical staff made up of field specialists.
Scottish private schools are committed to providing a school environment that will prepare children and "arm" them with the skills they need to succeed, however the future may be.
At this time, it cannot be denied that in a global business environment, languages continue to have a vital importance for the future of the country, so this should be reflected in education.
Modern languages should really be considered as "the ability of international communication".
Private schools will continue to offer this choice, diversity and excellence to young people in Scotland.
It has to be done.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Council of Private Schools.
