North Korea says it will not disarm 'in any way' unilaterally without gaining confidence
North Korea's foreign minister told the United Nations that the sanctions, which continued on Saturday, were deepening mistrust of the United States and the country would not unilaterally give up its nuclear weapons in such circumstances.
Ri Yong Ho told the annual body from around the world of the General Assembly that North Korea has taken "significant measures showing good will" in the past year, such as banning nuclear and missile tests, dismantling areas where nuclear tests were taking place, and pledging not to arm itself.
"However, we are not seeing any response to this from the U.S.," he said.
"Without trust in the U.S., our national security will have no self-confidence and under these circumstances there is no way for us to unilaterally disarm ourselves first."
While Ri reiterated North Korea's usual complaints about Washington's resistance to a split "phased" approach to the nuclear disarmament process where North Korea would be appreciated because of the gradual steps it has taken, his statement seemed significant because it did not rule out a breach.
The young man referred to a joint statement issued by Kim Jong Un and Donald Trump at a summit held for the first time between a sitting U.S. president and the North Korean leader in Singapore on June 12, where Kim pledged to work toward "nuclear disarmament of the North Korean peninsula" with the rival Trump.
North Korea has called for an official end to the 1950-53 Korean War, but the United States has said that Pyongyang must initially give up nuclear weapons.
Washington has also resisted calls to ease tough international sanctions on North Korea.
"The U.S. insists that nuclear disarmament is initially carried out and increases the level of pressure through sanctions to achieve their goal compulsorily, even by opposing the declaration of an end to the war," Ri said.
"The perception that sanctions can bring us to our knees is a dream in the sun of people who are uninformed about us.
But the problem is that the continuation of sanctions is deepening our mistrust."
Ri did not mention plans for a second summit between Kim and Trump, a statement the U.S. leader made earlier this week at the United Nations.
Instead, the minister underlined three meetings between Kim and South Korean leader Moon Jae-in in the past five months and added: "If the party to the issue of nuclear disarmament were South Korea and not the US, the process of nuclear disarmament on the Korean peninsula would not have come without this situation."
Despite this, the tone used in the New Address was profoundly different from last year when he told the UN General Assembly that the targeting of U.S. territory with North Korean missiles was inevitable after "Mr. President the Devil" Trump himself called Kim "a raccoon."
This year at the United Nations, Trump, who last year threatened to "totally destroy" North Korea, thanked Kim for the courage shown in taking steps to disarm, but said there was still a lot of work to be done and that sanctions should continue to be in place until North Korea does.
On Wednesday, Trump said he did not have a timeline for this, saying "If it takes two years, three years or five months - it doesn't matter."
China and Russia argue that the U.N. Security Council should reward Pyongyang for the steps it has taken.
U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo told the U.N. Security Council on Thursday that "the implementation of the Security Council's sanctions must continue vigorously and unabated until we carry out the full and final verification of nuclear disarmament."
The Security Council has unanimously decided to increase sanctions on North Korea since 2006, in an effort to end funding for Pyongyang's nuclear and ballistic missile programs.
Pompeo met with Ri on the sidelines of the UN General Assembly and then said he would visit Pyongyang again next month to prepare for a second summit.
Pompeo has visited North Korea three times already this year, but his last visit didn't go so well.
He left Pyongyang in July saying there had been progress, and only within hours North Korea denounced him as having carried out "mafia-style demands."
North Korea pledged in a meeting with Moon this month to disarm a missile zone and also a nuclear complex if the United States would take "appropriate measures."
He said Kim had told him that the "appropriate measures" he was seeking were security assurances Trump pledged in Singapore and moves toward normalizing relations with Washington.
Harvard students are given lessons on how to get enough rest.
A new course at Harvard University this year has involved all students to sleep more, in an effort to combat the growing culture of study 'masks' through the use of caffeine by these 'sleepers'.
One academic noted that students at the world's number one university often don't know when it comes to the most basic things about how to take care of themselves.
Charles Czeisler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at Brigham and Women's Hospital, prepared the lecture course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the US.
He was inspired to start this course after giving a review on the impact that sleep deprivation has on learning.
"At the end of it, a girl came up to me and said, 'Why are you telling me this now, in my last year?'
She said no one had told her before about the importance of sleep - which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, included in the program for the first time this year, explains to students the essential elements of how good sleep habits help academic and athletic performance, and also how it improves their overall well-being.
Paul Barreira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and the university's director general of medical services, said the university decided to introduce this course after finding that students were seriously deprived of sleep throughout the week.
The course that lasts an hour includes a variety of interactive tasks.
On one side is a view of a dorm room, where students click on coffee cups, curtains, athletes and books in order to explain to them the effects of caffeine and lighting and how athletic ranking is affected by lack of sleep, as well as the importance of the bedtime routine.
In another part, participants were explained how sleep deprivation in a long-term period increases the risks of heart attack, ischemia, depression and cancer.
A camp map, with interactive icons, further encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
"We know that students' behaviours will not change immediately.
But we believe they have a right to know - as you have a right to know, the health impact when you choose to smoke," Professor Czeisler added.
The culture of pride to spend “a sleepless night” continues to exist, he said, adding that modern technology and ever-increasing pressure on students meant that sleep deprivation was an ever-increasing problem.
Ensuring you get enough sleep, of a good quality, should be the students' 'secret weapon' to fight stress, fatigue and anxiety, he said - even to avoid weight gain, because sleep deprivation leads the brain into a mode of hunger, making them feel thirsty.
Raymond So, a 19-year-old Californian studying physical and chemical biology, helped Professor Czeisler prepare the course after attending one of his classes last year during his first year at Harvard.
He said the course had opened his eyes and inspired him to turn it into a course for the whole camp.
He hopes that the next step is to ask all postgraduate students to complete a similar study program before joining the competing institutions.
Prof Czeisler recommended that students should set a ringing clock that when they should go to bed, and also that when they should wake up, and be aware of the damaging effects of 'blue light' coming out of electronic screens and LED lighting, which can bring out the biological rhythm of sleep in the out-of-work setting.
