HIV/AIDS: China reports 14% increase in new cases
China has reported a 14% increase in the number of people living with HIV and AIDS.
There are more than 820,000 people affected across the country, health authorities say.
In the second quarter of 2018 alone, about 40,000 new cases were reported.
Most of the new cases have been transmitted through sexual intercourse, showing a difference from the past.
Traditionally, the HIV virus spread rapidly in some parts of China as a result of infected blood transfusions.
But the number of people receiving the HIV virus through this method had almost gone to zero, Chinese health officials said at a conference in Yunnan province.
However, year after year, the number of people living with HIV and AIDS in China has increased by 100,000 people.
HIV transmission through sex is an acute issue in the LGBT community in China.
Homosexuality was decriminalized in China in 1997, but discrimination against LGBT people is said to still prevail.
Because of the country's conservative values, studies have measured that 70-90% of men who have sex with other men will eventually marry women.
Most of the transmission of the disease occurs due to inappropriate protective measures during sex in these relationships.
Since 2003, the Chinese government has promised universal access to medical drugs for the treatment of HIV as part of an effort to tackle this problem.
