Emotions on the subject have been extremely high, and many Republicans have publicly stated that they want to continue voting for the candidate.
These things can't be broken," Grant Reeher, a professor of political science at Syracuse University's Maxwell School told The Hill about an article published Saturday.
Reeher said he doubted Senator Jeff Flake's last-minute effort to investigate by the FBI and that it would be enough to appease angry voters.
"Women won't forget what happened yesterday - they won't forget it either tomorrow or November," Karine Jean-Pierre, a senior adviser and national spokesperson for the progressive group MoveOn, said on Friday.
On Friday morning, protesters chanted "November is coming!" as they were demonstrating in the Senate corridors as Republicans in control of the Judiciary Committee decided to move forward with Kavanaugh's candidacy despite evidence from Dr. Christine Blasey Ford.
"Democratic enthusiasm and motivation will peak," Stu Rothenberg, an independent political analyst, told the news site.
"People are saying it's already been at high levels; that's true.
But it can be even higher, especially among undecided women voters in the periphery and among young voters, aged 18 to 29, who, although they don't like the president, usually don't vote at all."
Even before Ford's public testimony detailing her allegations of sexual assault against the Supreme Court candidate, analysts suggested there would be a backlash if Republicans continued to support this candidacy.
"This has turned into a convoluted confusion for the GOP," Michael Steele, the former chairman of the Republican National Committee, said earlier this week, according to NBC News.
"It's not just about the committee vote or the final vote or whether or not Kavanaugh will be placed in the defendant's bank, it's also about the way the Republicans dealt with this issue and the way they treated that woman," Guy Cecil, the Democratic leader of the US-backed Priorities, told NBC News.
However, Americans seem to be somewhat divided as to who to believe in the vigilance of Ford and Kavanaugh's evidence, with the latter having a slightly higher support.
A recent survey by YouGov shows that 41 percent of respondents believe Ford’s testimony is unquestionably or very likely, while 35 percent say they believe Kavanaugh’s testimony is unquestionably or very likely.
Also, 38 percent think Kavanaugh, most likely or most certainly, has lied during his testimony, while only 30 percent say the same about Ford.
Following Flake's insistence, the FBI is currently investigating claims made by Ford as well as other accuser, Deborah Ramirez, reports The Guardian.
Last week, Ford testified before the Senate Judiciary Committee, under oath, that Kavanaugh assaulted him at the age of 17 while he was in a drunken state.
Ramirez claims the Supreme Court candidate showed his genitals in front of her while they were at a party while they were studying at Yale in the 1980s.
The creator of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new internet to compete with Google and Facebook.
Tim Berners-Lee, the creator of the World Wide Web, is creating a company that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, ‘Inrupt,’ is a company built from Berners-Lee’s open-source platform, called ‘Solid.’
‘Solid’ allows users to choose where their data is stored and which persons are allowed to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokingly said that the goal after Inrupt is "world domination."
"We have to do it now," he said of this innovative company.
"It's a historic moment."
The app uses Solid's technology to allow people to create "storage of their personal data on the network" or a POD.
It may contain contact lists, lists of things to do, music lists, and other personal and professional tools.
It's the same as having available in a browser and at the same time Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify.
What is unique about storing personal data on the network is the fact that it remains entirely in the hands of the user what type of information they will access.
The company calls this "personal empowerment through data."
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company's CEO, John Bruce, is to bring together the right resources, processes and skills to help Solid be available to anyone.
The company currently consists of Berners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform purchased by IBM, several developers contracted to work on this project, and a community of volunteer coders.
Starting this week, technology developers around the world can create their own decentralized applications using the tools available on Inrupt's website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether or not to introduce a total change where all of their business models are completely overturned overnight.
"We're not asking for their permission."
In a Medium post published on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt's mission "is to provide commercial energy and an ecosystem that helps protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid."
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he founded the World Network Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
Over the past few months, Berners-Lee has been an influential voice in the network's inequality debate.
While founding Inrupt, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, the Network Foundation and the Open Data Institute.
"I'm extremely optimistic about this new era of the network," Berners-Lee added.
Bernard Vann celebrates the giving of the Victorian Cross during the First World War to the clergy
The only clergyman to have won a Victorian Cross during World War I as a warrior is commemorated in his birthplace, 100 years later.
Lieutenant Colonel Bernard Vann won the medal on 29 September 1918, in the attack on Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
However, he was killed by a sniper four days later and never found out that he had won the highest British military title.
A memorial stone was unveiled by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire, on Saturday.
One of the grandsons, Michael Vann, said it was "extremely symbolic" that the memorial would be displayed exactly 100 years from the heroic act that gave the medal to his grandfather.
According to the London Gazette, on 29 September 1918, Lieutenant Colonel Vann led his battalion through the Saint-Quentin Canal "through a dense fog and under the hail of bullets from the fields and machine guns."
He then rushed to the line of fire and with "great courage" led the battalion forward and captured one of the weapons on the battlefield and alone killed three people from opposing troops.
Vann was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918 - just over a month before the end of the war.
Michael Vann, 72, said his grandfather's actions "are something he can never achieve but something that really shows modesty."
He and his brother, Dr. James Vann, set off from a crown after the parade, which was led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth group.
Michael Vann said he "felt quite honored to be part of this parade" and added that "the value of a true hero is being shown by the support that is being given to him by many people."
