Desert Island Discs: Tom Daley felt ‘inferior’ about his sexuality
Olympic diver Tom Daley says he grew up feeling inferior to others because of his sexuality - but this gave him the motivation to succeed.
The 24-year-old said he didn't understand it until he went to nine-year-old school that "not everyone was like me."
Speaking on Radio 4's "Desert Island Discs," presented by Lauren Laverne, he said he raised the voice for gay rights to give "hope" to others.
He also said that after becoming a parent, he thought less about winning Olympic medals.
The permanent host of the long-term program, Kirsty Young, has taken a few months off because she is ill.
Appearing as an outcast on Laverne's first show, Daley said that while growing up he felt "inferior" to others because "it was not socially acceptable for you to like boys and girls."
He said: "Until today, those feelings of inferiority, and the fact that I felt different, were the real elements that gave me the push and the strength to cope."
He wanted to prove that he was worth "something," he said, so that he wouldn't disappoint everyone when they found out about his sexual orientation.
A two-time Olympic bronze medallist, he is already a high-profile LGBT activist and used his participation in the Commonwealth Games in Australia to appeal more to countries to legitimize homosexuality.
He said he came out open because he felt lucky to be able to live open and without consequences and wanted to give others "hope."
The three-time world champion said falling in love with a man - American film producer Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 - "caught me unprepared."
Last year, Daley married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, but said the age difference was never a problem.
"When you experience so many things at such a young age" - he went to the first Olympics at the age of 14 and his father died of cancer three years later - he said it was difficult to find someone at the same age who had experienced the same upsurge.
The couple became parents in June, to a boy named Robert Ray Black-Daley and Daley said his "whole perspective" had changed.
"If you had asked me last year, all I thought was 'I have to win a gold medal,'" he said.
"You know what, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
"My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son bears the same name as his father, Robert, who died in 2011, at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with head cancer.
Daley said his father didn't accept that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if we had tickets ready for London 2012 - because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him ‘that you won’t be able to be a front row dad,’” he said.
"I was holding his hand as he stopped breathing and only after he stopped breathing and changed his life and accepted for the first time that he was not invincible," he said.
The following year Daley competed at the 2012 Olympic Games and won the bronze medal.
"I knew this was what I'd dreamed of all my life - diving in front of the local public at the Olympics, there was no better feeling," he said.
Also, this inspired his first musical selection - Proud by Heather Small - which accompanied him during preparations for the Olympics and continues to cause him a nightmare.
Desert Island Discs will be broadcast on BBC Radio 4 on Sunday at 11:15 a.m.
