The National Trust observes the secret life of the nudes of the night
A new research being conducted by a company in Scotland's mountainous areas aims to uncover how night owls use the terrain to hunt for food.
It is hoped that the new findings will shed new light on the behavior of unique flying mammals and will help protect activities in the future.
The study by scientists at the National Trust for Scotland will follow common night owls and those called soprano pipestrelles as well as brown-eared and Daubenton owls in the Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording equipment will be placed at key points throughout the area to track the activities of night nudists throughout the season.
NHS staff and volunteers will also conduct field studies using hand-held detectors.
The analysis of the sounds that will be carried out by experts for all recordings will determine the frequency of the sounds of night owls and what each species does.
Then, a report and a map of their habitat will be drawn up to give a detailed overview of their behavior.
Rob Dewar, Nature Conservation Advisor for NTS, hopes the findings will reveal which habitats are most important to night owls and how they are used by each species.
This information would help determine the benefits of managing habitats, such as the creation of pastures and how to maintain forests for night owls and other related species.
The number of night owls in Scotland and across the UK has dropped significantly over the past century.
They are under threat from construction and development works that bring impact to the nests and habitat loss.
Wind turbines and lighting can also pose a risk, as shown by adhesive sheets or chemical components of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic animals.
The night owls are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use a sophisticated location-finding technique through sounds to accurately determine insects and obstacles during flight.
The NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 important gardens and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes nudity very seriously.
There are ten trained experts, who regularly conduct studies, speech inspections, and are sometimes involved in rescue programs.
The organisation has even set up Scotland's first and only night owl reserve in Threeve, Dumfries and Galloway, which serves as home to eight of Scotland's ten night owl species.
The reserve's administrator, David Thompson, says the country is the ideal territory for them.
"Here at Threea we have a great area for night owls," he said.
"We have old buildings, a lot of old trees and all the right habitat.
But there's still a lot of stuff about night owls that remains unknown, so the work we're doing here and elsewhere will help us understand more about what they need to 'develop'."
He stresses the importance of carrying out inspections for nudity the night before carrying out the maintenance works of the property because there is a possibility that the unintentional destruction of a nest can kill up to 400 female and young nudity thus wiping out the entire population of an area.
Night owls are protected, and killing, harassing, and disturbing them or destroying their speech is illegal.
Elisabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee with the Night's Watch Trust, encourages people to become part of the relief.
She said: "We still have a lot to learn about our night owls and many of our species, we just don't know how their population is shifting."
