Brexit: UK 'will regret forever' the loss of the status of car manufacturers
The UK will "repent forever" if it loses its status as the world leader in post-Brexit car manufacturing, business secretary Greg Clark said.
He added that it was "worrying" that Toyota in the UK had told the BBC that if Britain left the EU without a deal, the company would temporarily stop production at its factory in Burnaston, near Derby.
"We need a deal," Clark said.
The Japanese automaker said the impact of delays at the border, in the event of a no-deal exit, would cost jobs lost.
The plant in Burnaston - which makes the Toyota Auris and Avensis models - produced nearly 150,000 cars last year, 90% of which were exported to other European Union countries.
"In my judgment, if Britain leaves the EU at the end of March, we will stop production at our factory," said Marvin Cooke, Toyota's managing director at Burnaston.
Other carmakers in the UK, such as Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have also expressed fears about leaving the EU without a deal and how cross-border trade will work.
For example, BMW said that after Brexit it will close its Mini series factory for a month.
The main concerns relate to what car manufacturers refer to as supply chain risks in the event of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota's production line operates on a "as soon as ordered" basis, with parts coming every 37 minutes from UK and EU suppliers for custom cars.
If, on 29 March, the UK leaves the EU without a deal, there may be border delays which, according to this industry, could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to keep at its factory in Derbyshire the inventory of more than a day, the company said, and as a result production will stop.
Mr Clark said Theresa May's Chequers plan for future relations with the EU "is built specifically to avoid these border checks."
"We need a deal. We want to have the best deal that will allow us not only to enjoy the success of the moment but also to take advantage of this opportunity," he told BBC Radio 4's Today programme.
"The data, not only from Toyota but also from other manufacturers, shows that we definitely need to be able to continue what has been a pretty successful supply chain."
Toyota could not determine how long it would halt production, but in the long run, warned that increased costs would lower the plant's competitiveness and consequently lead to a reduction in jobs.
