Earthquakes and tsunamis in Indonesia
At least 384 people have died as a result of a powerful earthquake and tsunami that hit the Indonesian city of Palu on Friday, officials said as the death toll is expected to rise.
With communication networks out of service, aid workers have failed to get information from the Donggala regency, an area north of Palu, which was closest to the 7.5-sided quake epicenter.
In Palu, more than 16,000 people have been evacuated after the disaster.
Below are some facts about Palu and Donggala, on the island of Sulawesi:
Palu is the capital of the central Sulawesi province, located at the end of a narrow bay on the west coast of the island of Sulawesi, with a population of about 379,800 inhabitants, in 2017.
The city was celebrating its 40th anniversary when it was hit by an earthquake and tsunami.
Donggala is a regency stretching over more than 300 km (180 miles) along the coastline to the northwest of the island of Sulawesi.
The regency, a smaller administrative region than the province, had an estimated population of about 299,200 in 2017.
Fishing and farming are the province's main economic activities, especially in the coastal region of Donggala.
Nickel mining is also important in the province, but it is mainly concentrated in Morowali, on the other side of the Sulawesi coast.
According to Indonesia's Disaster Mitigation Agency, Palu and Donggala have been hit several times by the tsunami over the past 100 years.
In 1938, a tsunami killed more than 200 people and destroyed hundreds of homes in Donggala.
In 1996, another tsunami hit the western part of Donggala, causing nine casualties.
Indonesia is located in the seismic zone of the Ring of Fire in the Pacific Ocean and is regularly hit by earthquakes.
Below are some of the biggest earthquakes and tsunamis of recent years:
2004: On December 26, a powerful earthquake on the western coast of Aceh province in Indonesia, in northern Sumatra, caused a tsunami that struck 14 states, causing 226,000 casualties along the Indian Ocean coastline, of which more than half live in Aceh.
2005: A series of powerful earthquakes hit the west coast of Sumatra in late March and early April.
Hundreds died on the island of Nias Island, off the coast of Sumatra.
2006: A 6.8-magnitude earthquake struck southern Java, Indonesia's most populous island, causing a tsunami that hit the southern coast and claimed the lives of about 700 people.
2009: A 7.6-magnitude earthquake near the city of Padang, the capital of western Sumatra province.
More than 1,100 people died.
